| <#itemstack-wrapper>          | <#itemstack-wrapper-method>          |
| <#itemstack-null>             | <#itemstack-null-method>             |
| <#itemstack-ingredient>       | <#itemstack-ingredient-method>       |
| <#itemstack-itemlike>         | <#itemstack-itemlike-method>         |
| <#itemstack-resourcelocation> | <#itemstack-resourcelocation-method> |
| <#itemstack-stringtag>        | <#itemstack-stringtag-method>        |
| <#itemstack-json>             | <#itemstack-json-method>             |
| <#itemstack-string>           | <#itemstack-string-method>           |
| <#itemstack-default>          | <#itemstack-default-method>          |

# To `IntProvider`

>>> #intprovider-number
`[java]Number`, JS `number`
<<<

>>> #intprovider-number-method
Will result in an `[java]ConstantInt` provider that provides the specified constant number converted to integer.
<<<

>>> #intprovider-list
`[java]List`, JS array
List must not be empty
<<<

>>> #intprovider-list-method
Will result in an `[java]UniformInt` provider.
Its minimum is the first element of the list.
Its maximum depends on the length of the list:
- If it has 2 elements or more, maximum is the second element of the list.
- Otherwise (the list has only one element), maximum will be equal to minimum.

Effectively, the conversions will happen as follows for these examples (`[js]_` means that this element is ignored):
- `[js]\[min\]` (`[js]max = min`)
- `[js]\[min, max\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _, _, _, /* … */, _\]`
<<<

>>> #intprovider-map
`[java]Map<String, Object>`, JS `object`
(examples will use JS object syntax)
<<<

>>> #intprovider-map-method
## Int bounds parsing
If the object is `[js]\{ bounds: \[min, max\] \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformInt` provider. Its minimum will be the first element (`[js]min`) of the list, its maximum will be the second element (`[js]max`) of the list  at the `bounds` key. Note that the elements of the list will be parsed from string. If parsing fails, __**it does so silently**__ and the default value of `[js]0` is used. Also, the list length is unchecked. If the list is shorter than 2 elements, an `[java]IndexOutOfBoundsException` will be thrown.

If the object is `[js]\{ min: minVal, max: maxVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformInt` provider. Its minimum will be the number value at the `min` key (`minVal`), its maximum will be the number value at the `max` key (`maxVal`).

If the object is `[js]\{ min_inclusive: minVal, max_inclusive: maxVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformInt` provider. Its minimum will be the number value at the `min_inclusive` key (`minVal`), its maximum will be the number value at the `max_inclusive` key (`maxVal`). (Yes, that's the exact same method as the previous object, just different key names)

If the object is `[js]\{ value: val \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformInt` provider. Its minimum and maximum will be the number value at the `value` key (`val`).

If the object does not conform to any of the above schemas, `[js]null` is returned.

---

The object provided will be treated as `[java]Map<String, Object>`.
Then, [int bounds are parsed](#int-bounds-parsing).
If the resulting object is not `[js]null` (and thus the object conforms to one of the schemas):
- The returned `[java]UniformInt` provider is returned.
Else, if the object contains the `clamped` key, thus the object looks like for example:
```js
{
	clamped: {
		min: 20,
		max: 50,
	}
}
```
- The object inside the `clamped` key has its [int bounds parsed](#int-bounds-parsing), then the outer object itself has its [int bounds parsed](#int-bounds-parsing). As the outer object's int bounds are parsed as `[js]null` (or else, the first case would pass), nothing is returned here, and the next case is checked.
Else, if the object contains the `clamped_normal` key, thus the object looks like for example:
```js
{
	clamped_normal: {
		mean: 20,
		deviation: 10,
	}
}
```
- The outer object has its [int bounds parsed](#int-bounds-parsing).
- Then, the provider's mean becomes the number at the `mean` key converted to integer.
- Then, the provider's deviation becomes the number at the `deviation` key converted to integer.
- As the outer object's int bounds are parsed as `[js]null` (or else, the first case would pass), nothing is returned here, and the next case is checked.

If all the checks above fail, the object is wrapped into an NBT compound tag and passed into the vanilla `[java]IntProvider.CODEC` to be hopefully decoded into an `[java]IntProvider`.
<<<


>>> #intprovider-default
Other types
(including non-conformant `Map`s and `object`s)
<<<

>>> #intprovider-default-method
Will result in a `[java]ConstantInt` provider that provides `[js]0` (__**fails silently!**__).
<<<

| From type                        | Method                                  |
| <#intprovider-number>            | <#intprovider-number-method>            |
| <#intprovider-list>              | <#intprovider-list-method>              |
| <#intprovider-map>               | <#intprovider-map-method>               |
| <#intprovider-default>           | <#intprovider-default-method>           |

# To `FloatProvider`

>>> #floatprovider-number
`[java]Number`, JS `number`
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-number-method
Will result in an `[java]ConstantFloat` provider that provides the specified constant number converted to 32-bit float.
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-list
`[java]List`, JS array
List must not be empty
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-list-method
Will result in an `[java]UniformFloat` provider.
Its minimum is the first element of the list.
Its maximum depends on the length of the list:
- If it has 2 elements or more, maximum is the second element of the list.
- Otherwise (the list has only one element), maximum will be equal to minimum.

Effectively, the conversions will happen as follows for these examples (`[js]_` means that this element is ignored):
- `[js]\[min\]` (`[js]max = min`)
- `[js]\[min, max\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _, _, _, /* … */, _\]`
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-map
`[java]Map<String, Object>`, JS `object`
(examples will use JS object syntax)
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-map-method
## Float bounds parsing
If the object is `[js]\{ bounds: \[min, max\] \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformFloat` provider. Its minimum will be the first element (`[js]min`) of the list, its maximum will be the second element (`[js]max`) of the list  at the `bounds` key. Note that the elements of the list will be parsed from string. If parsing fails, __**it does so silently**__ and the default value of `[js]0` is used. Also, the list length is unchecked. If the list is shorter than 2 elements, an `[java]IndexOutOfBoundsException` will be thrown.

If the object is `[js]\{ min: minVal, max: maxVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformFloat` provider. Its minimum will be the number value at the `min` key (`minVal`), its maximum will be the number value at the `max` key (`maxVal`).

If the object is `[js]\{ min_inclusive: minVal, max_inclusive: maxVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformFloat` provider. Its minimum will be the number value at the `min_inclusive` key (`minVal`), its maximum will be the number value at the `max_inclusive` key (`maxVal`). (Yes, that's the exact same method as the previous object, just different key names)

If the object is `[js]\{ value: val \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformFloat` provider. Its minimum and maximum will be the number value at the `value` key (`val`).

If the object does not conform to any of the above schemas, `[js]null` is returned.

---

The object provided will be treated as `[java]Map<String, Object>`.
Then, [float bounds are parsed](#float-bounds-parsing).
If the resulting object is not `[js]null` (and thus the object conforms to one of the schemas):
- The returned `[java]UniformFloat` provider is returned.
Else, if the object contains the `clamped_normal` key, thus the object looks like for example:
```js
{
	clamped_normal: {
		mean: 20,
		deviation: 10,
	}
}
```
- The outer object has its [float bounds parsed](#float-bounds-parsing).
- Then, the provider's mean becomes the number at the `mean` key converted to integer (sic!).
- Then, the provider's deviation becomes the number at the `deviation` key converted to integer (sic!).
- As the outer object's float bounds are parsed as `[js]null` (or else, the first case would pass), nothing is returned here, and the next case is checked.

If all the checks above fail, the object is wrapped into an NBT compound tag and then passed into the vanilla `[java]FloatProvider.CODEC` to be hopefully decoded into an `[java]FloatProvider`.
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-default
Other types
(including non-conformant `Map`s and `object`s)
<<<

>>> #floatprovider-default-method
Will result in a `[java]ConstantFloat` provider that provides `[js]0` (__**fails silently!**__).
<<<

| From type                | Method                          |
| <#floatprovider-number>  | <#floatprovider-number-method>  |
| <#floatprovider-list>    | <#floatprovider-list-method>    |
| <#floatprovider-map>     | <#floatprovider-map-method>     |
| <#floatprovider-default> | <#floatprovider-default-method> |

# To `NumberProvider`

>>> #numberprovider-number
`[java]Number`, JS `number`
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-number-method
Will result in an `[java]UniformGenerator` whose min and max is set to the provided number converted to a 32-bit float.
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-list
`[java]List`, JS array
List must not be empty
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-list-method
Will result in an `[java]UniformGenerator`.
Its minimum is the first element of the list.
Its maximum depends on the length of the list:
- If it has 2 elements or more, maximum is the second element of the list.
- Otherwise (the list has only one element), maximum will be equal to minimum.

Effectively, the conversions will happen as follows for these examples (`[js]_` means that this element is ignored):
- `[js]\[min\]` (`[js]max = min`)
- `[js]\[min, max\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _\]`
- `[js]\[min, max, _, _, _, /* … */, _\]`
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-map
`[java]Map<String, Object>`, JS `object`
(examples will use JS object syntax)
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-map-method
If the object is `[js]\{ min: minVal, max: maxVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformGenerator`. Its minimum will be the number value at the `min` key (`minVal`), its maximum will be the number value at the `max` key (`maxVal`).

If the object is `[js]\{ n: nVal, p: pVal \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]BinomialDistributionGenerator`. Its `n` will be set to the number value at the `n` key (`nVal`) converted to an integer, its `p` will be the number value at the `p` key (`pVal`) converted to a 32-bit float. The `n` and `p` relate to the parameters of the [binominal distribution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution).

If the object is `[js]\{ value: val \}`:
- Will result in an `[java]UniformGenerator`. Its min and max will be set to a number value at the `value` key converted to a 32-bit float.
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-default
Other types
(including non-conformant `Map`s and `object`s)
<<<

>>> #numberprovider-default-method
Will result in a `[java]ConstantValue` provider that provides `[js]0` (__**fails silently!**__).
<<<

